<h2>A Note About Choosing Investors and Advisors</h2>
We meet people every day and I interview investors for Venture Hacked on a frequent basis. I love meeting different personalities getting behind different views related to entrepreneurship and investment. But, my meeting with Rob was different than most.

5 minutes into the conversation, Rob had somehow convinced me that I needed him on my team. Mentor? Advisor? Investor? The funny part is that I’m wasn’t even looking.

As a startup CEO, when evaluating investors, advisors, or mentors, you should look for that magical click that makes you believe you can be business partners with that person/those people. And, hopefully the feeling is mutual. One would hope you share the same vision, aspirations, and communication styles so that the relationship lasts a long lifetime (or at least a decade).

The concept of taking time to find the right investors fits into the hire slow, fire fast mentality that most startup CEOs don’t take the time to do when fundraising.

As entrepreneurs, I think we’d all be better off if we began thinking of investors along these lines. We’d have a much better chance of success, much like you have a much better chance of success growing your startup if you hire the right employees.

Rob’s responses to my questions are similar to those you should look for when interviewing investors. Actually, they are better than most. Hopefully this article also gives you a better idea of what you might look for in an investor or advisor.

